                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 3.  <span>Major coevolutionary events in the intersexual arms race of <em>Acilius.</em></span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec2.fig2.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec2.fig2.caption1.p1"></a><p>Top row: close-up of female cover wings, bottom row: male front foot with suction cups. 1: The ancestor of <em>Acilius</em> evolved a back with dense and large punctures accompanied in males by large cup size differentiation into three large and multiple smaller cups. 2: Females evolve setose furrows, males further differentiate their suction cups, one very large, two medium sized and radically increasing the number of minute cups. 3: The last transformation reverse in both sexes supporting the theory that arms races can both escalate and de-escalate <a href="#pone.0000522-Arnqvist3">[43]</a>. 4: The female, but not male, condition also reverses in the recent species <em>A. kishii</em>.</p>
